<h1>@HI{{nado}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} <strong>@HI{{nado}}</strong> ... 
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{nado}}</strong> is used to terminate a non-exhaustive list of nouns. It is often used in conjunction
with <a href="grammar-particle-ya.html">@HI{{ya}}</a>.
of nouns.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha,@KT{{ringo}}yamikannyabanana<strong>nado</strong>,kudamononara@KJ{{what}}demo@KJ{{fond}}kidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I like any kind of fruit: apples, oranges, bananas.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{nado}}</strong> can be used to indicate a tentative suggestion.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{come^week}}no@KJ{{trip^going}}ha@KJ{{box^root}}<strong>nado</strong>doudesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      How about Hakone for next week's trip?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

